Headingley washout is setback in bid to entice Yorkshire fans
A first-day washout in the second Test against New Zealand was the last thing Yorkshire wanted as they attempt to “reinvent” Headingley and their new chief executive, Mark Arthur, has warned against English cricket’s “unsustainable” model of maintaining 11 international grounds.
Rain prevents play: The first day of the second Test between England and New Zealand was washed out at Headingley Photo: REUTERS	By Nick Hoult, Headingley
7:33PM BST 24 May 2013
Follow Comments
Umpires Steve Davis and Aleem Dar were forced to abandon play for the day without a ball being bowled shortly before 4pm, by which time the ground was virtually empty. Ticket holders on Friday will get a full refund or a ticket to next year’s Sri Lanka Test. The England and Wales Cricket Board is covered by rain insurance and Arthur said there would be “minimal” losses for Yorkshire, primarily from sales in the club shop, as the Leeds Rugby Club hold the pouring rights to the bars. With an encouraging weather forecast for the weekend, a crowd of 12,000 is expected on Saturday with 7-8,000 attending on Sunday.
Arthur took over at Yorkshire with a brief to ensure Headingley remains a big player in the battle to stage England matches. There are now 10 grounds, with Taunton also looking to join the list of venues for international cricket in this country.
Competition is fierce but the difficulty of staging international cricket and making it pay was underlined recently when Durham gave up two one-day internationals, fearing they would take a financial loss on the matches.
Lord’s and Trent Bridge are now the market leaders in staging Test cricket, but Arthur is concerned a north-south divide could develop if clubs such as Yorkshire start to miss out on matches.
