“When I last worked in cricket there was a rota basis so you could set your business plans according to when you knew you would miss out on a particular Test match,” said Arthur, a former chief executive of Nottinghamshire and Nottingham Forest. “On an eight-year programme you would know what you were going to get. Now there is a huge bidding process with 10, soon to be 11, grounds and it is unsustainable.
“There is a finite amount of international cricket in this country. To spread it among 11 international grounds and expect all those grounds to be at the same level as the top international grounds around the world doesn’t work, does it? What are we all after? It is a sustainable game of cricket at club, county and international level. We all have to work together for that balance.
“One of the best things that happened to football was the reconstruction of Wembley because for a period of time England took their games around the country. They connected with more people. That is one of the unique factors of international cricket in England. It does get taken around the country and I think it is important to understand that not everybody has the spending capacity of those people who live in the South-East of the country. That has to be factored in when they are allocating matches. There is a finite amount of money that you can charge for cricket out in the provinces.” The cheapest adult ticket at Headingley on Friday for this match against New Zealand was £40 and Arthur has agreed he will review pricing policy before next year’s Test. The problem he has to solve is enticing the Yorkshire public back to the ground. There are more than 40,000 club cricketers in Yorkshire but selling international match tickets is a challenge for the club.
Headingley has a staging agreement with the ECB for regular England matches until 2019 but there are no guarantees after that, and Arthur knows a half-full ground does not project the right image.
“We have to make sure by that point [2019] people are seeing Headingley in a totally different light,” he said. “It is up to us to reinvent Headingley as the great cricket ground and stager of international cricket that it was in the past.
“We have to improve our ability to sell tickets, the capacity of the ground and the environment of the ground. The spectator experience when they first arrived at the gate is absolutely vital.”
Arthur intends to spend the winter visiting clubs to work out why there is a “disconnect” between Headingley and cricket supporters. “There must be something that is amiss. We have got work to do and we recognise that. Fundamentally we have to grow a base of cricket supporters who want to support cricket matches at Headingley. “Trent Bridge has proved once you are in a sell-out situation the demand for tickets is always that much greater. People always want a ticket for something they can’t get to and we have to improve our supporter base. We have to get more people engaged with Headingley and then we can start taking on other events.”
